<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Headline turns the page for Hodder
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AUTHORS such as television personality Cilla Black and champion jockey Peter
Scudamore are teaming up with Winston Churchill, John Buchan and John le
Carre.
Such diverse talent is being brought under one roof in a Pounds 48.9m
takeover by seven-year-old upstart Headline Book Publishing of the stately
125-year-old Hodder &amp; Stoughton.
The recommended offer is likely to create in Hodder Headline the second
largest independent UK publisher after Macmillan. It will be worth close to
Pounds 100m.
Mr Tim Hely Hutchinson, the 39-year-old founder of Headline, said yesterday
that substantial savings would flow from the deal. Hodder Headline would
also have greatly increased resources to move aggressively in the
marketplace.
'If it makes sense to offer an author a Pounds 3m multi-book deal we will do
it,' said Mr Hely Hutchinson, who will be group chief executive.
Headline, a specialist in popular commercial publishing, has 76.8 per cent
acceptances for the privately held Hodder shares. Most of the 120
shareholders are descended from founders of the company, set up as an
evangelical publisher. Hodder shareholders are being offered 37.5 new
Headline shares for each of theirs. The paper offer is worth Pounds 108.75 a
share, the partial cash version Pounds 90. Headline is also raising Pounds
12.8m in a four-for-nine rights issue at 240p a share.
The merged group will move into new central London headquarters but the two
sales forces will remain separate. Hodder's wide range of publishing - from
general fiction and non-fiction to children's books and religion - will be
retained.
Although both companies are trading profitably, exceptional merger costs
might lead to a pre-tax loss this year.
Apart from stepping up in size, Headline is getting access to a profitable
backlist of more than 5,000 titles. And the venerable Hodder is also way
ahead of Headline in 'non-book' products, ranging from audio and video tapes
to CD-Roms.
Hodder is about to launch Worshipmaster, a product that could revolutionise
the lives of Church of England vicars. The computer programme will produce
suitable texts, readings and hymns for specific Sundays of the year.
Mr Philip Attenborough and Mr Patrick Wright, who have run Hodder, will
become deputy chairman and deputy chief executive respectively of Hodder
Headline.
</TEXT>
