<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Equities fall in wake of
rising gold prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US STOCKS fell in subdued trading yesterday in the wake of a rally in gold
prices and some disappointing news on the jobs market, writes Patrick
Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 8.58 at 3,544.87. The
more broadly based Standard&amp;Poor's 500 ended 1.10 lower at 452.75, while the
Amex composite finished up 0.94 at 440.91, and the Nasdaq composite up 0.36
at 706.22. Trading volume on the NYSE was 280m shares.
Rising gold prices took their toll on equities right from the opening. The
price of August gold contracts jumped Dollars 5.40 to Dollars 376.30, an
indication that some investors continue to fear a revival in inflation.
Concern about the employment situation also hurt stocks after the Labor
department reported that the number of people claiming state unemployment
insurance rose 5,000 last week, to 344,000. The figures indicate that
today's May employment report could reveal that the labour market remains
depressed, in spite of the growing economy. Wall Street analysts are
predicting that today's report will show a rise of about 50,000 in non-farm
payrolls, and national unemployment still stuck at 7 per cent.
One of the more eye-catching of new issues in recent months - the sale by
Sears, Roebuck of 20 per cent of its stake in Allstate, the insurance
company - was in strong demand. In the largest ever initial public offering
by a US company, 78.5m shares in AllState were issued at Dollars 27 a share
on Wednesday night. By the close yesterday, the stock was trading at Dollars
29 3/8 in volume of 26m shares.
Federal Express fell Dollars 4 3/8 to Dollars 45 1/2 after broking house
Donaldson Lufkin Jenrette lowered its rating on the stock from 'buy' to
'moderately attractive' in the wake of recent managerial resignations.
Computer stocks were mixed. While Hewlett-Packard gained Dollars  7/8 to
Dollars 86 3/4 and Compaq put on Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 61 1/8 , Digital
Equipment fell Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 43 7/8 and Tandem Computer slipped
Dollars  1/2 to Dollars 13.
Both Digital and Tandem were hit by ratings downgrades by securities house
Salomon Brothers.
Fieldcrest Cannon climbed Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 28 5/8 on the news that
it is selling its carpet and rug operations to Mohawk Industries in a deal
valued at Dollars 140m.
Canada
TORONTO closed higher in busy trading, as a surge in world gold prices sent
gold-related stocks higher and helped boost the overall market.
The TSE 300 composite index rose 15.19 points, or 0.39%, to close at
3875.01.
Consumer products posted the day's biggest decline, off 1.6%, as Seagram,
the group's biggest stock, fell 1 1/4 to 34 1/8 . The company yesterday
reported a small improvement in first-quarter earnings, but said interest
expenses for its recent investment in Time-Warner Inc. would eat into cash
flow.
</TEXT>
