<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / UK Company News: Norcros drops 26% and calls for Pounds
49.7m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NORCROS, the building products manufacturer, yesterday announced a 2-for-7
rights issue raising Pounds 49.7m net to take advantage of the property
upturn, as it unveiled a 26 per cent fall in pre-tax profits for the year
ended March 31.
The shares are being offered at 132p - a substantial discount to the
existing share price which slipped 3p to 165p on a day the market also fell.
Pre-tax profits declined from Pounds 15.6m to Pounds 11.5m after an
exceptional charge of Pounds 4.5m (Pounds 100,000) to cover the cost of
restructuring. The workforce was reduced by a further 700 to about 7,000.
The group plans to use the rights proceeds to reduce borrowings and to make
bolt-on acquisitions to its core business of building products. Debt fell by
Pounds 7.9m to Pounds 120.2m resulting in a lower interest charge of Pounds
6.3m (Pounds 8.6m).
Mr Michael Doherty, chairman, said the group was well placed to take
advantage of any upturn in the UK.
While it remained committed to disposing of its property portfolio, recently
valued at Pounds 45m, Mr Doherty said the rights proceeds would enable it to
sell at a more leisurely pace.
Property disposals during the year amounted to Pounds 16.9m. A provision for
the fall in value of the disposed property was mainly responsible for an
extraordinary charge of Pounds 7.9m.
Operating profits fell from Pounds 24.3m to Pounds 22.3m on reduced sales of
Pounds 389.7m (Pounds 394m).
Those from building products increased from Pounds 3.56m to Pounds 7.76m;
ceramics saw a reduction from Pounds 11.3m to Pounds 7.4m and printing and
packaging reported Pounds 10.6m (Pounds 12m).
The final dividend is held at 3.5p making an unchanged total of 7p. Earnings
per share fell from 7.5p to 5p.
COMMENT
Given the history of false dawns in the building sector it would be
surprising if investors did not treat the latest optimistic soundings from
Norcros with more than a dollop of scepticism. The UK recovery already
appears to be faltering and borrowings, notwithstanding the rights issue,
will remain quite high. However, the results of the restructuring, resulting
in the loss of a further 700 jobs, puts the company on a better footing
should the UK experience a sustained upturn. Analysts estimate that every
pound in sales should yield 33p in operating profits. Faced with a choice of
either selling property or tapping shareholders for cash the latter was
preferable. With forecast pre-tax profits of Pounds 19.5m the shares are on
a prospective multiple of 17.6, and shareholders should probably give the
company the benefit of the doubt one more time.
</TEXT>
