<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / DTI was asked to probe Alpine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Department of Trade and Industry was asked in February to launch an
inquiry into events at Alpine (Double Glazing), which ceased trading earlier
this week.
A solicitor's letter written on February 12 on behalf of some franchisees
and former employees called on the DTI to investigate the activities and
administration of Alpine. This was almost a year after Alpine was purchased
out of administration by a group of investors backed by Mr Clive Smith, the
Midlands entrepreneur.
Mr Smith, who has a number of off-shore trusts, has been connected to
several natural resource companies, two of which are being investigated by
the Serious Fraud Office.
The solicitors told the DTI in February their investigations had 'caused
considerable concern about the financial stability of Alpine'. They drew
attention to questions over the alleged transfer of monies.
They also queried pension payments deducted from salaries, since Alpine did
not have an approved pension scheme.
Furthermore, the letter states, one former employee represented by the
solicitor had access to bank statements which he claims show that over
Pounds 600,000 was transferred out of Alpine following its purchase.
It also emerged yesterday that a creditor owed Pounds 30,000 had lodged a
petition to wind up Alpine, due to be heard on June 16.
However, Alpine's directors recently instructed an insolvency practitioner
to call a creditors meeting to vote on liquidation the day before that
petition is heard.
