<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / Smith faces attack from union chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH will come under veiled attack this weekend from the general
secretary of Britain's third-largest union for lacking boldness and
imagination as Labour party leader.
In a keynote speech to his annual conference on Sunday, Mr John Edmonds,
general secretary of the 860,000-strong GMB general union, will denounce
Labour's failure to seize the political opportunities provided in the past
12 months by the troubles of Mr John Major's government.
Although Mr Smith will not be criticised directly - because Mr Edmonds wants
to avoid personalising the issues - the speech is likely to be interpreted
as the first damaging public attack on the Labour leader from one of the
union leaders whose block votes ensured his victory in last autumn's
leadership election.
Mr Smith is a member of the GMB and has attended the conference for the past
three years, but Mr Edmonds has not invited him to speak to the delegates
this year.
The GMB, traditionally a centre-right union loyal to the Labour leadership,
appears under Mr Edmonds to have become a critic of the present state of the
Labour movement.
Mr Edmonds claims to have discovered widespread disillusionment and
discontent among union activists across the country in recent months, and he
intends to articulate their views.
He will argue that both the Labour party and the trade unions have lacked
focus for their attacks on the Conservatives. His speech will question
whether Labour's caution and patience have been a sensible way of responding
to what he regards as the government's wickedness.
The GMB general secretary is unlikely to compromise over the controversial
issue of one member, one vote for the selection of Labour parliamentary
candidates and election of the party leader and deputy leader.
Mr Smith has turned the issue into a test of his political credibility.
Mr Edmonds insists that union political levy-payers must have a voice in
such elections inside the Labour party through their affiliated unions,
arguing that Labour has a federal structure and is more than just a party of
individual members.
The union is also likely to give no comfort to those in the Labour party who
want to carry through parliamentary electoral reform like proportional
representation in parliamentary elections.
The GMB is expected to defend the existing first-past-the-post system of
electing MPs.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
