<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / The Lex Column: MEPC
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Things have reached a pretty pass when the City expresses disappointment
after a company eschews a dilutive rights issue. Such is the intoxicated
haze surrounding the property sector, that MEPC's abstinence comes as
something of an anti-climax. MEPC may be sticking to the commendable view
that diluting net asset values is a heinous offence. But it has not ruled
out the possibility. The suspicion remains that the summer will not pass
without it tapping the market.
The danger is that, without fresh funds, MEPC will be left behind in a
recovering property market. With gearing in excess of 80 per cent and thin
cash flow, MEPC has only limited scope to upgrade its assets and diversify
its portfolio. Its interim results suggest it may yet have to rely on
property disposals to justify a maintained annual dividend.
So far, the stock market has wafted most companies in the property sector
higher on a surge of sentiment. But the point must soon be reached where
differences in asset quality and growth prospects produce a marked
divergence in share performance. Those companies using cheap money to buy
properties yielding 9 per cent will usefully bolster income and increase
their exposure to any growth in asset values. Land Securities, British Land
and Brixton Estate, have already positioned themselves to benefit. MEPC must
decide whether it dares follow suit.
</TEXT>
