<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / Extension of loan regulation urged: OFT backs move on credit
to small businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LENDING to small businesses by banks and other financial services companies
should be licensed under the Consumer Credit Act, Sir Bryan Carsberg,
director-general of fair trading, said yesterday. The aim was to ensure that
such lending was done fairly.
Sir Bryan said there was a case for extending to small incorporated
businesses the level of statutory protection for loans of up to Pounds
15,000 now given to individual borrowers under the 1974 act.
However, Sir Bryan rejected proposals from the Department of Trade and
Industry to impose further restrictions on credit marketing and said he
believed regulation under the 1974 act should be simplified.
Disclosing the initial results of an OFT review, Sir Bryan said he favoured
amendments to non-statutory rules to ensure that consumers were protected
from unscrupulous traders. He said the Banking Code of Practice, which is
being reviewed by a committee of the British Bankers' Association, should
include a 'best advice' provision to ensure that customers were advised
correctly on the choice between deposit accounts and insurance-based
products.
The code should also require banks and building societies to give fair
advice when counselling customers on choosing a repayment mortgage or an
endowment mortgage on which the organisation stood to gain an insurance
commission.
Sir Bryan, speaking to a Building Societies Association conference in
Brighton, said most of the government's proposals made in December 1990 to
extend restrictions on credit marketing should 'not be taken forward'. There
was 'significant scope for deregulation' by simplifying provisions of the
act, he said. This would then enhance the credit licensing system as a tool
to ensure high standards.
Sir Bryan said after his speech that he believed there was little logic in
loans of up to Pounds 15,000 to unincorporated small businesses being
subject to the act while similar loans to incorporated companies were not
regulated.
He believed many such businesses would benefit from the act because they
were relatively unsophisticated. 'Many of them are just a man or a woman
running a shop who were not expert in the ways of credit,' he said.
The act restricts the terms under which personal loans and overdrafts can be
advertised. It also requires lenders to provide information on the annual
percentage charge (APR) for loans.
Sir Bryan faced criticism from the head of the largest independent financial
adviser in the country over his recent report suggesting that the
non-disclosure of commissions attached to life insurance products restricts
competition.
Mr Geoffrey Lister, chief executive of Bradford &amp; Bingley Building Society,
told the conference that proposals for independent financial advisers could
'lead to the virtual disappearance' of such advice.
</TEXT>
