<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / Litany of charges against Invesco detailed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Pounds 750,000 fines levied yesterday on Invesco MIM by Imro, the
self-regulating body for fund management organisations, with costs of Pounds
1.6m, are a record for an SRO disciplinary case.
The more painful punishment for the group is the litany of charges Imro
published yesterday.
The first charge states that between July 1988 and December 1992, Invesco
MIM Management (IMM) 'failed to take reasonable steps to ensure that its
officers and employees acted in conformity with their own and their
employer's relevant responsibilities under the regulatory system'. IMM also
failed to 'ensure it had in place internal controls and systems adequate for
the size, nature and complexity of its activities'.
IMM also paid money which was not clients' money into a client money
account, and breached regulations on the handling of clients' money. It
provided 'inaccurate' information to Imro and issued a misleading
advertisement.
The second set of eight charges relates to Invesco MIM Unit Trust Managers
(IMUTM). The first says 'in or about May 1990, Invesco notified Imro of a
pricing error in respect of shares held by a unit trust scheme but did not
reveal how the error had arisen or its scale.'
Another charge is that between April 1988 and April 1990 IMUTM valued a fund
incorrectly.
Further charges said between January 1989 and November 1991, IMUTM failed to
ensure that only client money was held in designated client bank accounts,
and between September 1987 and September 1992, it made an investment on
behalf of an authorised unit trust which was outside the trust's objective.
The third set of 20 charges was brought against Invesco Ventures, covering
issues such as carrying on business outside permitted areas, breaches of
rules pertaining to customer title documents, defective record-keeping,
provision of inaccurate regulatory information, financial resource
deficiencies, failure to provide investors with accurate and timely
information and undisclosed conflicts of interest made on behalf of
customers.
The penultimate set of charges was against Invesco Ventures and Invesco MIM
Management. These say unsuitable investments were made by IMM and IVL on
behalf of customers, who subsequently suffered losses.
The fifth set of three charges covers IMM's conduct in relation to assets
belonging to the Mirror Group Pension Scheme, plundered by the late Mr
Robert Maxwell.
The charges state IMM failed to keep Imro properly informed of its concerns
about how the pension fund's assets under IMM's management were being used.
They say IMM failed to disclose to the pension fund trustees that it no
longer had custody of investments it was managing on their behalf.
The other charge says that on 19 October 1990, IMM, in custody of
certificates on investments valued at Pounds 26.7m belonging to 'some of its
customers', parted with their possession of those certificates to a third
party other than on the instructions of the customers.
</TEXT>
