<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / Adviser fined over home-income plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DBS Financial Management, the UK's largest independent financial adviser
group, has been fined Pounds 60,000 by Fimbra, the self-regulating
organisation for independent financial advisers.
The fine relates to the activities of Sandy Park Financial Services, an
appointed representative of DBS, and its sale of home-income plans in the
period 1988 to 1990. The plans were devised as a way for (mostly elderly)
investors to unlock capital in their homes by remortgaging their homes and
investing the proceeds in the hope of earning enough to meet mortgage
payments with extra income on top.
Some firms, including Sandy Park, backed the plans with single-premium
investment bonds. When the value of the bonds fell and interest rates rose,
investors suff-ered financial difficulties.
In addition to paying the fine and costs, DBS must write to remaining
home-income clients of Sandy Park and advise them to consider taking
professional advice. DBS is continuing to defend legal actions instituted in
connection with home-income plans.
DBS terminated its relationship with Sandy Park in April 1991, and the group
says it has taken firm action to strengthen any possible gaps in compliance
or monitoring procedures.
The announcement was unusual in that it was made by the disciplined
organisation rather than by the regulator. Shares in DBS Management, DBS's
parent company, are traded on the Stock Exchange under rule 535(2) and the
company said it felt it was appropriate to inform shareholders.
Fimbra said it would not comment until the end of the legal period in which
DBS is entitled to appeal.
</TEXT>
