<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / Dundee united in derisive thumbs-down: The Timex plant may
close now that strikers have rejected the peace plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YESTERDAY'S unanimous rejection by the Timex strikers of a peace plan
negotiated by their union to end their four-month strike reflects how
attitudes have hardened.
But the strikers may have lost their only opportunity to resolve the dispute
with some semblance of victory.
Their derisive thumbs-down after less than half an hour of emotional debate
is a bitter blow to the AEEU engineering union. Mr Jimmy Airlie, the union's
Scottish executive officer, had negotiated hard with Timex's management over
the past fortnight in search of a compromise deal he believed the strikers
could live with.
What he presented to the 340 strikers in Dundee yesterday was the best he
believes the company will offer. A one-year wage freeze may have been hard
for them to swallow as well as cuts in fringe benefits - it has been
calculated that the deal would have been equivalent to a 27 per cent
reduction in living standards.
But Mr Airlie pointed with some satisfaction to concessions he had extracted
from the company, not without difficulty. For Timex to offer jobs back for
all strikers and not just rehire selectively was a genuine breakthrough.
Timex also accepted that it should pay statutory minimum redundancy to those
who did not want to be re-employed, which Mr Airlie told the strike meeting
was a 'unique' concession in his long experience.
It is hard for the union's national leadership to know what to do next. 'We
have no options left,' said one official.
None of the full-time union officials outside Dundee believe they can do
anything that will ensure any kind of victory. 'The trouble is we are
dealing with virgin strikers. They have suffered a grave injustice by all
being sacked and they see no good reason why they should compromise to get
their old jobs back,' said another official.
The strikers' resolute stance will strengthen the hand of Timex's local
manager Mr Peter Hall. It was his decision to fire all the workers in
January and replace them with a new labour force when they refused to accept
much smaller cuts in their pay and benefits than are now being demanded.
Last night Mr Hall made clear the company's offer would not be improved.
There have been differences on how to resolve the strike between Mr Hall and
Mr John Dryfe, the US-based Timex director responsible for the company's
circuit board business, who was himself once in charge of the Dundee plant.
Mr Hall has hinted that he wants to re-employ selectively from the strikers.
He seems to have no genuine desire to see all of them back inside the plant,
particularly the shop stewards whom he blames for the deterioration of
industrial relations.
But when Mr Bill Jordan, the union president, and Mr Airlie made a private
appeal to the company, Timex decided to see whether a settlement could be
negotiated.
Since January the strike has become a cause celebre not just in the British
Labour movement but across the world. Achieving a deal was seen by some in
the company as an important move in helping to restore Timex's tainted
image.
After yesterday the company has three options. One is to go on as before,
recruiting a larger substitute workforce and ignoring the strikers. Another
is to go back to the bargaining table with the union and improve the offer.
But there is also a final option that many in Timex management outside
Dundee might start to consider - closing the plant. Circuit board production
is not part of the company's core business and it loses money. Mr Dryfe says
it was mainly for sentimental reasons that the company stayed in Dundee,
introducing circuit board manufacture, after shifting watch production to
France 10 years ago.
The strike leaders have often declared that if they do not win, they would
prefer to see the plant closed.
If the dispute drags on to autumn and beyond, this may become an
increasingly attractive option for a company that feels hard done by and
believes it has done all it can to resolve one of the most bitter strikes
seen in Britain for years.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
