<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / BA pilots vote for stoppages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PILOTS AT British Airways have voted by a five-to-one majority in a secret
postal ballot to take strike action.
The ballot is a further blow to the company which last night was facing the
prospect of a 24-hour strike today by its 17,000 cabin crew and ground staff
worldwide.
In a 92 per cent turnout, the pilots voted 2,152 in favour with only 402
against.
If the pilots strike all BA's 207 long- and short-haul craft would be
grounded. Balpa, the pilots' union, estimates that BA would suffer Pounds
16m in lost fares for each strike day.
Mr Chris Darke, the union's general-secretary, said last night the ballot
result showed 'the depth of ill-feeling among our members'.
Mr Darke added: 'The massive response and overwhelming majority for strike
action indicates pilots are deeply dissatisfaction with the way BA are
seeking to impose changes without agreement.'
Mr Darke said he had written to Mr Robert Ayling, BA's chief executive,
demanding an immediate resumption of talks with the company over the pilots'
worries.
The union is concerned at what it sees as the company's attempt to divide
pilots by introducing separate contracts of employment in its Gatwick
subsidiary, which was set up last November after BA's takeover of Dan Air.
Pilots in the subsidiary are paid 30 per cent less than those elsewhere in
British Airways.
At Gatwick, 90 pilots voted for strike action and only seven were against.
Negotiations were continuing yesterday evening between BA and the TGWU
transport union to try to avert a 24-hour strike by cabin crew and ground
staff due to start at midnight over the alleged cut in pay and fringe
benefits in BA's subsidiaries.
BA's 250 white-collar supervisory, clerical and passenger service staff are
also due to strike at Gatwick airport today.
</TEXT>
