<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / S African all-race poll date proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH AFRICAN politicians yesterday recommended a date next April for the
first all-race elections, but said the date must be confirmed in multi-party
talks later this month.
They named April 27, 1994, as the date for elections to a constituent
assembly and interim legislature - the first time a specific date has been
mentioned - but attached so many conditions to it that the date remains
largely symbolic.
The 26-party negotiating forum was unable to reach full agreement even on a
conditional resolution setting a date, with four delegations rejecting the
resolution. They were the KwaZulu government, speaking on behalf of Chief
Mangosuthu Buthelezi, along with the ultra-right Conservative Party, the
moderate-right Afrikaner Volksunie and the black homeland of Ciskei.
But Mr Cyril Ramaphosa, secretary general of the African National Congress,
claimed a strategic victory nonetheless: 'Setting the 27th of April as an
election date will reverberate throughout the country. Even those opposed to
confirming it will find it impossible to move the masses of our people away
from this date,' he told reporters after a 10-hour negotiating session.
Mr Ramaphosa and his ANC colleague, Mr Joe Slovo, who represents the South
African Communist Party in the talks, were obviously keen to set a date,
however provisional, before next week's meeting of the ANC national
executive.
Yesterday's announcement of a provisional date could have major
psychological implications. The negotiators' resolution said it would 'send
a ray of hope and optimism' to South Africans, desperate for any sign of a
political solution which could restore stability.
Even if the date is agreed, no elections can be held until the parties agree
on an interim constitution.
</TEXT>
