<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / Ukraine call to become nuclear state
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   KIEV
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UKRAINIAN Prime Minister Leonid Kuchma said yesterday that Ukraine should,
at least temporarily, become a nuclear power, according to MPs who listened
to his speech at a closed session of parliament.
Mr Kuchma, former director of the world's largest missile factory, urged
parliament to ratify the Strategic Arms Limitation Treaty, which covers 130
of the 146 Inter-Continental Ballistic Missiles on Ukrainian territory, but
to postpone accession to the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty as a
non-nuclear state.
'Ukraine must confirm itself temporarily as a nuclear state,' one MP quoted
Mr Kuchma as saying. The 46 ICBMs Mr Kuchma suggests Ukraine should
temporarily keep were built at his factory in the Ukrainian city of
Dnipropetrovsk.
According to MPs, Mr Kuchma also said that Ukraine has the technical
capacity to develop operational control over the 46 SS-24s on its territory.
Currently, all the ICBMs stationed in Ukraine are under Russian control, but
Mr Kuchma's statement suggests that Ukrainian leaders may be seeking to
develop independent nuclear capacity.
Mr Kuchma's speech is the first time a Ukrainian government official has
openly called for Ukraine to become a nuclear power, even temporarily.
His position, which earned him tumultuous applause from the legislature,
could be the harbinger of a major toughening of the Ukrainian policy on
nuclear weapons.
While asking for security guarantees and financial compensation, in the past
the Ukrainian government has categorically asserted that it would ratify
both Start 1 and the NPT.
But Mr Dmytro Pavlychko, chairman of the parliamentary commission on foreign
affairs, said that now Ukraine would hold out for air-tight security
guarantees before giving up all of its nuclear missiles.
'We can consider accession to the NPT, but only when we have an air-tight
treaty on security guarantees,' Mr Pavlychko said. 'The west will not want
to give us such guarantees and it will take a long time before they come
around.
'We want to drag out the disarmament process,' he said. 'Not just for seven
years (the period specified by Start 1) but for much longer.'
It is unclear whether Mr Kuchma's assertion is a reflection of his own
perspective as a former maker of missiles, or signals a wider change in
government policy.
Just a few hours earlier, the Foreign Minister Anatoli Zlenko had urged MPs
to ratify both Start 1 and NPT, warning that failure to do so could carry
serious international repercussions.
Mr Kuchma's break with the official government line lends credence to the
concerns recently expressed by US officials that Ukraine could be seeking
independent control over its nuclear arsenal.
The prime minister's statement, which came on the eve of a visit to Kiev by
the Russian foreign minister and a few days before US defence secretary Les
Aspin is due to come to Kiev, is likely to exacerbate Ukraine's already
strained relations with both the US and Russia.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>UAZ  Ukraine, East Europe.
</CN>
