<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JUN 93 / Sharp drop in west German GDP
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WESTERN Germany's gross domestic product fell by a real 3.2 per cent in the
first quarter of the year, compared with the same period of 1992. It was the
sharpest drop in economic activity since 1975.
The figure was immediately seized upon by Mr Gunter Rexrodt, economics
minister, as confirmation that Germany could be facing its most severe
recession for more than 30 years.
He warned that the downturn could jeopardise recovery in eastern Germany,
which is heavily dependent on western investment. He called for urgent
measures to control inflation and limit public spending, to provide room for
further cuts in interest rates to stimulate a recovery.
Yet the Bundesbank, whose governing council yesterday decided against any
further rate reductions, cautioned against excessive pessimism about the
figures.
Mr Otmar Issing, a leading director of the bank, said the figure was
distorted by special factors. Economic activity in the first quarter of 1992
was exceptionally favourable, thanks to a particularly mild winter; and
there was a surge in consumer spending in the last quarter of the year,
before a one percentage point increase in value added tax on January 1.
A second set of figures just released, for manufacturing activity in April,
showed a better than expected recovery of 0.5 per cent compared with March.
The March figure was also adjusted upwards, and the two-month total showed
an increase of 1 per cent against January-February.
All categories of economic activity in the GDP were down in the first
quarter, however, with the sharpest fall (14.8 per cent year-on-year)
recorded for investment in plant and equipment. Private consumption was down
1 per cent, state consumption down 1.4 per cent, while imports and exports
both showed sharp declines: 5.4 and 6.3 per cent respectively.
Gross national product, which includes external trade, showed an even
sharper decline than GDP, down by a real 3.7 per cent over the year.
Mr Rexrodt said the figures confirmed his repeated view that 'the current
recession in western Germany could prove more serious than those in the
1960s, the 1970s and the beginning of the 1980s'. He said there was 'still
no concrete sign of a turn in the economy'.
His gloom contrasted with the more relaxed attitude of Mr Helmut
Schlesinger, the Bundesbank president, in Bonn on Wednesday, when he warned
against a 'mood of black despair', and insisted that the slump in industrial
production was no more dramatic than in the past recessions of 1973-75 and
1980-82.
On the other hand, the German trade union federation called for an emergency
DM30bn (Pounds 12bn) economic growth initiative to counter rising
unemployment, and for the Bundesbank to take immediate action to 'loosen its
interest-rate stranglehold' on the entire European economy.
</TEXT>
