<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / Drink suppliers to open market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK's largest carbonated drink suppliers yesterday agreed to give
undertakings aimed at guaranteeing competition in the soft drinks industry,
nearly two years after they were first recommended by a Monopolies and
Mergers Commission report.
Coca-Cola Schweppes Beverages, Coca-Cola Bottlers (Ulster), and Britvic  -
which together account for more than half the UK's Pounds 5.5bn carbonated
drinks market - agreed to end exclusive or restrictive supply agreements
with pubs and leisure outlets.
Coca-Cola Schweppes also agreed to seek approval from the Office of Fair
Trading before it acquired any business involved in supplying draught soft
drinks through dispensing machines.
Mr Neil Hamilton, corporate affairs minister, asked for the undertakings
last June. His request followed consultation between the Department of Trade
and Industry and the companies, after a commission report on the carbonated
drinks market published in August 1991.
The report found competition was generally effective in the take-home trade,
but that practices in the leisure trade could restrict choice and lead to
higher prices.
Mr Hamilton called the undertakings a 'very satisfactory outcome'.
Coca-Cola Schweppes, a joint venture between the US Coca-Cola Company and
Cadbury Schweppes of the UK, which has 30 per cent of the carbonated drinks
market, said the undertakings would have 'no significant impact' on its
business as they affected only about 1 per cent of its sales volume.
Britvic, owned by brewers including Bass, Whitbread and Allied Lyons, which
has about 20 per cent of the UK market, said the undertakings would have 'no
effect on its ongoing business'.
</TEXT>
