<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / Planned increase in terror premiums condemned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER and MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMMERCIAL insurance buyers yesterday condemned swingeing increases in
premiums for terrorism insurance planned by Pool Re, the government-backed
reinsurance company.
The government announced last Friday that it would press Pool Re to increase
rates for policies starting after July 1, following the IRA bombing of
Bishopsgate in the City in April.
According to a letter sent to one leading UK company by the Department of
Trade and Industry, large London-based businesses will face increases of
more than 300 per cent.
The Association of Insurance and Risk Managers in Industry and Commerce,
which represents commercial insurance buyers at more than 300 UK companies,
says moves to penalise city-centre businesses, particularly those in London,
is 'short sighted and could prove counter-productive'. The association said
it would prefer 'the traditional and proven insurance involving the
spreading of risk. It is more equitable.'
The Confederation of British Industry also renewed warnings to the
government about the potential impact on business of raising terrorism
insurance premiums on City and West End properties by up to 300 per cent.
The DTI letter said: 'The most significant change is the removal of the
discounts which had previously been given for large sums insured. We
concluded that while this may be an appropriate approach for fire insurance,
it is unsuitable for terrorism insurance.'
An 'extra large' property based in central London and valued at Pounds 500m
would pay Pounds 720,000 for its terrorism insurance after the revision
compared with between Pounds 175,000 and Pounds 262,500 before. A 'very
large' central London property worth Pounds 100m would pay Pounds 144,000
(Pounds 51,000-Pounds 76,000), while a 'small' building in central London
(valued at Pounds 1m) would pay Pounds 1,400 (Pounds 900-Pounds 1,350).
Smaller properties outside central London would benefit from lower rates.
</TEXT>
