<DATE>930603
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / BT takes global step with Dollars 4.3bn US deal: MCI agrees
to joint venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH TELECOM and MCI of the US yesterday made a bold bid for leadership
of the international telecommunications industry. BT is to take a Dollars
4.3bn (Pounds 2.8bn) stake in MCI, the second largest US carrier, and set up
a Dollars 1bn joint venture with it in a development that could reduce
significantly the cost of trans- atlantic calls.
BT will take 20 per cent of MCI and put up three-quarters of the capital for
the joint venture, which is designed to exploit the fast-growing market
among multinational companies for international voice and data transmission
services.
The moves will not delay the sale of the UK government's remaining tranche
of BT shares, the prospectus for which will be issued at the end of this
month as previously planned.
Coming a week after American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, the largest US carrier,
launched its Worldsource venture to exploit the global market, the new
alliance will intensify the battle between AT&amp;T and BT and MCI for
international custom.
Mr Iain Vallance, BT's chairman, said the investment and joint venture lay
at the centre of the company's strategy 'to become a leading global provider
to multinationals'.
Under the deal, BT will put up Dollars 830m immediately; the balance will
come from cash and borrowings, offset by the Dollars 1.8bn BT expects to
receive in this financial year from the sale to AT&amp;T of McCaw, its US
cellular telephone subsidiary. BT will gain three directors on the MCI
board; the chairman of MCI, Mr Bert Roberts, will join the BT board.
BT is paying an average of Dollars 64 a share for its MCI stake, a premium
on the Dollars 52 closing price on Tuesday. As part of the deal, MCI is
taking over most of BT's North American assets.
The joint venture, to be located in either Washington or London, will
eventually subsume Syncordia, BT's US-based global outsourcing operation.
Apart from attracting business, it will undertake research and development
for the two companies, providing a 'global platform' for value added
services such as frame relay and outsourcing.
Mr Roberts said the alliance was 'indicative of future opportunities' in the
telecommunications industry, and would help MCI to continue its growth in
the US domestic market while competing on the world market.
Both companies stressed the link-up would not affect existing relationships
with other international carriers, and made light of potential regulatory
hurdles. US regulations limit foreign ownership of a US carrier to 25 per
cent.
Talks between the two companies, which already have close commercial links,
have been progressing for several years. 'BT thought they could conquer the
US; MCI thought it could conquer the world,' said Mr Roberts, explaining why
an alliance had not materialised earlier.
Last night, Moody's, one of the big US debt rating agencies, said it was
considering downgrading about Dollars 8.7bn of long debt at British Telecom,
in the wake of the MCI deal. However, the agency also said that it would
consider raising MCI's debt rating, given the company's 'potential for an
improved operating profile and increased financial flexibility'.
In New York, BT ADRs closed down Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 65 1/8 , while MCI
shares gained Dollars 1 5/8 at Dollars 54 3/8 , a 52-week high. AT&amp;T shares
were unchanged by the close, at Dollars 62, having fallen initially on the
news. In London, the City reacted cautiously to the announcement. The move
was thought to make strategic sense for the UK carrier, but institutional
investors were concerned about the price paid for the MCI stake and likely
returns. BT's shares closed 5p down at 421 1/2p.
BT was advised by N M Rothschild and MCI by Goldman Sachs.
