<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / World Stock Markets (America): US prices flat as May jobless
data awaited
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices ended mostly flat as investors turned their attention toward
tomorrow's eagerly-awaited May employment report, writes Patrick Harverson
in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 1.11 at 3,553.45, a
fraction short of its all-time high. The more broadly based Standard&amp;Poor's
500 ended 0.02 firmer at 453.85, while the Amex composite finished 1.37
higher at 439.97, and the Nasdaq composite up 1.52 at 705.80.
Trading volume on the NYSE was 287m shares. After Tuesday's solid gains,
prices opened lower in light trading, although by mid-afternoon they had
crept back into positive territory. In the absence of a lead from the bond
market, which held steady, or from gold prices, which rebounded slightly
after the previous day's big declines, investors focused on the day's
economic news, and on tomorrow's release of May jobs data. This will give
the markets the latest reading on the current state of the economy.
Economic figures yesterday were inconclusive. April home sales, up 22.7 per
cent on the month, came in well above forecasts, and failed to lift prices.
Instead, investors paid more attention to the April index of leading
economic indicators, which showed a modest rise of 0.1 per cent. Analysts
had expected an increase of about 0.5 per cent.
MCI Communications, which is traded on the Nasdaq market, jumped Dollars 1
5/8 to Dollars 54 3/8 after announcing that it had sold a 20 per cent stake
to British Telecom for Dollars 4.3bn and agreed to establish a Dollars 1bn
joint venture to develop the two companies' North American
telecommunications businesses. ADRs in British Telecom fell Dollars 1 1/8 to
Dollars 65 1/8 . Tambrands fell Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 43 after the
company warned second quarter earnings would fail to meet last year's
levels. Drug and healthcare stocks came under selling pressure. Syntex fell
Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 19 7/8 after the Food and Drug Administration
rejected its application to sell an over-the-counter version of its Naproxen
painkiller. Leading drug stocks elsewhere fell on reports that the release
of President Bill Clinton's healthcare reform proposals will probably be
delayed until July. Fear of prolongued uncertainty about the proposals left
Merck Dollars  5/8 lower at Dollars 37 1/4 , Schering-Plough down Dollars 1
7/8 at Dollars 65 1/8 , Johnson&amp;Johnson Dollars  1/2 weaker at Dollars 44
1/4 , and Bristol-Myers Squibb Dollars  3/8 off at Dollars 59 1/2 .
Healthcare stocks on the Nasdaq also tumbled.
Canada
TORONTO STOCKS closed steady in heavy trading. An active session closed
narrowly mixed as a recovery in oil and gas and precious metals issues
offset tumbling consumer products.
A plunge in heavily weighted Seagram Co shares took the consumer products
index down 97.19 to 6,262.31.
The TSE-300 finished 2.95 points higher at 3,859.82 on turnover of 76.54m
shares valued at CDollars 668.17m. Declines led advances 350 to 355, with
277 issues steady.
Seagram fell 1 1/8 to 35 3/8 in brisk trade. It posted operating net profit
of USDollars 0.43 per share versus USDollars 0.41.
</TEXT>
