FT  03 JUN 93 / International Company News: 'Number two' resigns from
Federal Express
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Tom Oliver, head of worldwide customer operations at Federal Express and
the effective 'number two' executive at the nation's largest overnight
delivery company, resigned yesterday. Mr Oliver said he was taking up the
post of chief executive and president of VoiceCom Systems, a San
Francisco-based voice processing services provider.
Also departing from Memphis-based Federal Express is Ms Carole Presley,
senior vice-president for marketing and corporate communications. She will
remain a consultant to FedEx but will start her own consulting business in
Florida.
Federal Express has suffered long-standing problems in its international
division and was forced retrench from an ambitious European expansion plan
last year. Since then, losses on the international front have been
diminishing, although competition has put pressure on domestic earnings.
Mr Oliver, 52, who had previously headed the international business, became
executive vice-president of worldwide customer operations in late-1991 when
chief operating officer, Mr James Barksdale, quit the company. Mr Oliver
subsequently oversaw much of the European restructuring action.
Yesterday, FedEx said Mr Oliver would be replaced by Mr William Razzouk,
currently senior vice-president of sales and customer service. Mr Fred
Smith, the company's founder, remains chairman.
