FT  03 JUN 93 / International Company News: Generali uses reserves to buy
two companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENERALI, Italy's biggest insurance company, is dipping into its cash
reserves to reinforce its dominant position in the domestic market by buying
two small insurance companies.
The group is purchasing 50 per cent of Risparmio Vita and majority control
of Risparmio Assicurazioni, two subsidiaries of Turin's big city savings
bank. The two companies have premium income of L19bn (Dollars 13m) and L22bn
respectively.
The acquisitions, part of a closer co-operation between the insurer and the
bank in financial services, follow last month's increase in Generali's stake
in its growing Hungarian operation.
EA Generali, the group's Vienna-based subsidiary, raised its stake in
Hungary's Providencia Versicherung to 75.1 per cent from 56 per cent.
Providencia, created in 1990, is Hungary's third biggest insurer, with
650,000 customers and total premium income of Ft5.6bn (Dollars 63m) in 1992.
Premiums are forecast to rise to Ft8bn this year. The Generali group is
already active in Hungary through its majority-owned Generali Budapest
subsidiary.
Providencia made a net loss of Ft495m in 1992 as a result of costs
associated with building up a branch network. The company hopes to break
even by 1995.
