<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / International Company News: Allstate's share offer largest
seen in US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Allstate, the second largest car and home insurer in the US and
previously a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Sears, Roebuck group, were
priced last night at Dollars 27. This is at the upper end of the indicated
price range for the flotation, which ranged between Dollars 24 and Dollars
27.
Last night's pricing makes the Allstate flotation the largest initial public
offering ever seen in the US. The company is selling 78.5m shares to outside
investors, including 10m to non-US investors. At the Dollars 27 price, this
will raise Dollars 2.12bn. Underwriters' over-allotment options, if
exercised, could take the total number of shares available to 89.5m.
Prior to yesterday's flotation of Allstate shares, the largest initial
offering in the US had come from Conrail. In 1987, the transportation group
raised Dollars 1.64bn.
In terms of all stock offerings - whether flotations or secondary offerings
 -the Allstate transaction ranks in third place, behind share sales by
British Petroleum and Time Warner.
The shares being sold by Allstate represent 20 per cent of the insurer's
equity. Sears, based in Chicago, will continue to hold the remaining 80 per
cent. Sears first announced plans to spin off a minority stake in Allstate
last year, as part of its general strategy of pulling out of financial
services and concentrating on its core retail business.
Sears has already sold a 20 per cent stake in Dean Witter, Discover, netting
about Dollars 800m, and announced sale plans for its Coldwell Banker
operations.
Allstate is the second largest writer of homeowners and car insurance
policies in the US, behind State Farm, also based in Illinois. State Farm,
however, remains a 'mutual' company, essentially owned by its policyholders.
Allstate is likely to become the second biggest quoted insurer in the US, in
terms of stock-market capitalisation, behind American International Group.
</TEXT>
