<HEADLINE>
FT  03 JUN 93 / International Company News: Metallgesellschaft falls to
DM98m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRE-TAX profits at Metallgesellschaft fell 39 per cent to DM98.3m (Dollars
60.3m) in the six months ended March, in spite of a 17 per cent surge in
sales.
In the light of 'negative' economic conditions, any improvement in the
second half would have to come from continuing cost-cutting programme, the
metals-based conglomerate said yesterday.
The group planned to press ahead with a disposal programme, announced
earlier this year by Mr Heinz Schimmelbusch, chief executive, who said he
aimed to raise DM1bn from such sales by the end of 1993-94.
Although the overall half-year result was unsatisfactory, some sectors, such
as engineering services subsidiaries Lurgi and Lentjes, produced markedly
better earnings. On the other hand, the BUS environmental services business
was hit when one of its important customers was driven into bankruptcy.
Turnover in the services businesses, which account for the bulk of group
sales, rose 12 per cent to DM9.3bn.
Together with a 48 per cent improvement in the industrial division's sales
to DM3.3bn, this advance wiped out reductions in raw materials and other
sectors, and pushed the group total up to DM13.9bn.
Performance at Buderus, which specialises in heating, construction products
and special steel, and forms the mainstay of the industrial division,
matched expectations with profits from all businesses except steel.
Dynamit Nobel, acquired along with Buderus early last year when
Metallgesellschaft bought the non-paper divisions of Feldmuhle Nobel from
Sweden's Stora, suffered especially from weak demand for plastic products
and high-performance ceramics.
Vehicle components maker Kolbenschmidt made a loss in the first half as
rationalisation measures failed to compensate for the downturn in automotive
markets.
Raw materials turned in an unsatisfactory result. Although productivity
improved in German smelting plants, they made significant losses as a result
of weak non-ferrous metals prices and disadvantageous exchange rates.
Investment, which was inflated by acquisitions in the first half of 1992-93
and down 54 per cent to DM1.7bn in the period under review, was focused
mainly on Kolbenschmidt, Dynamit Nobel and above all in the Buderus heating
business.
</TEXT>
